statement.p:
Let f and g be functions that satisfy
f'(2) = 6 and g'(2) = 7.  Find h'(2)
for each function h given below:

If 
f(t) =  \frac { \sqrt {2 }} {t ^{ 5 } }
find f'( t ).

If 
f(x) = \frac { 2 \sin x }{ 3 + \cos x }
find f'( x ).

static.solution:
Solution:
Use the Product Rule on each term.
\begin{array}{rcl} g'(t) \amp =\amp [(4 t^{6})(e^t) + (24 t^{5})(e^t)] + 1 [ (\sin t)(-\sin t) + (\cos t)(\cos t)] \\ \amp \amp \\ \amp =\amp 4 t^{5}(6 + t)e^t - 1 \sin^2 t + 1 \cos^2 t \end{array}

f'(x)=\frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{10\sin\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}{3x^{2}+10\sin\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}\right)=\frac{10\cos\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\mathopen{}\left(3x^{2}+10\sin\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\right)-10\sin\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\mathopen{}\left(6x+10\cos\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\right)}{\left(3x^{2}+10\sin\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\right)^{2}}=\frac{30x^{2}\cos\mathopen{}\left(x\right)-60x\sin\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}{\left(3x^{2}+10\sin\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\right)^{2}}
or
f'(x)=\frac{30 x[x \cos(x)-2 \sin(x)]}{[3 x^2 +10 \sin(x)]^2}

statement.p:
If 
f(x) =  \frac {\sqrt { x } - 3 }{\sqrt { x } + 3 } 
find f'( x ).

solution.me:
\begin{array}{rcl}
   f'(x) \amp =\amp  7 \sec x \tan x \\
   f''(x) \amp =\amp  7\big((\sec x)(\sec^2 x) + (\sec x \tan x)(\tan x)\big) \\
   \amp =\amp  7(\sec^3 x + \sec x \tan^2 x)
  \end{array}

static.solution:
Solution:
Use the Product Rule twice.
\begin{array}{rcl} f'(x) \amp =\amp x^{-9} \cdot \frac{d}{dx}[ e^x \sec x] + \frac{d}{dx}[ x^{-9} ] \cdot (e^x \sec x) \\ \amp =\amp x^{-9}\left( e^x \frac{d}{dx}[ \sec x ] + \frac{d}{dx}[e^x] \sec x \right) - 9 x^{-10} (e^x \sec x) \\ \amp =\amp x^{-9} (e^x( \sec x \tan x) + e^x \sec x) - 9 x^{-10} e^x \sec x \\ \amp =\amp x^{-9} e^x( \sec x \tan x) + x^{-9} e^x \sec x - 9 x^{-10} e^x \sec x \\ \end{array}

f(x)=\frac{5\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}+1\right)\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}{1-\cos\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\csc\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}=\frac{5\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}+1\right)\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}{1-\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}
Using the quotient rule to differentiate we get,
f'(x)=\frac{d}{dx}(\frac{5\mathopen{}\left(x^{2}+1\right)\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}{1-\cos\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\csc\mathopen{}\left(x\right)})=5\frac{\frac{d}{dx}[\left(x^{2}+1\right)\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)]\cdot (1-\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right))-\frac{d}{dx}[1-\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)]\cdot \left(x^{2}+1\right)\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}{(1-\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right))^2}
=5\frac{[2x\cdot \cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right) - \csc^{2}\mathopen{}\left(x\right) \cdot (x^{2}+1)]\cdot  (1-\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right))-[\csc^{2}\mathopen{}\left(x\right)]\cdot \left(x^{2}+1\right)\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)}{(1-\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right))^2}
=\frac{5\mathopen{}\left(2x\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)-\left(x^{2}+1\right)\csc^{2}\mathopen{}\left(x\right)-2x\cot^{2}\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\right)}{\left(1-\cot\mathopen{}\left(x\right)\right)^{2}}

statement.p:
Express the function y = \sqrt{ x^2 + 9 } 
as a composition y = f(g(x)) of two simpler
functions y = f(u) and u = g(x).

static.solution:
Solution:
Use the Chain Rule with inside function u = 14 x and outside function y = -8\csc u.
\begin{array}{rcl} f'(x) \amp =\amp \displaystyle\frac{dy}{du} \cdot \frac{du}{dx}\\ \amp \amp \\ \amp =\amp ( + 8\csc u \cot u)(14) \\ \amp =\amp + 112 \csc(14 x) \cot(14 x) \end{array}

Solution:
Use the Chain Rule with inside function u = \cos x and outside function y = \ln u.
\begin{array}{rcl} f'(x) \amp =\amp \displaystyle\frac{dy}{du} \cdot \frac{du}{dx}\\ \amp \amp \\ \amp =\amp \displaystyle \left(\frac{1}{u} \right)(-\sin x) \\ \amp \amp \\ \amp =\amp \displaystyle\frac{1}{\cos x} (-\sin x) \\ \amp \amp \\ \amp =\amp -\tan x \end{array}

Solution:
It may help to rewrite f(x) = [\sin (3 x)]^{7}. Use the Chain Rule with inside function u = \sin (3 x) and outside function y = u^{7}. A second application of Chain Rule is used to find \frac{du}{dx}.
\begin{array}{rcl} f'(x) \amp =\amp \displaystyle\frac{dy}{du} \cdot \frac{du}{dx}\\ \amp \amp \\ \amp =\amp (7 u^{6})(\cos(3 x) \cdot 3) \\ \amp =\amp 21 \sin^{6}(3 x)\cos(3 x) \end{array}

