static.solution:
Solution:
The two cars and the intersection form a right triangle. Let a = distance from the officer's car to the intersection (along the north-south street), and b = distance from the intersection to the other car (along the west-east street). Let c = straight-line distance from the officer's car to the other car. Then by the Pythagorean Theorem, a^2 + b^2 = c^2. Take time-derivatives of both sides of this equation. \begin{array}{rcl} \dfrac{d}{dt}\left[ a^2 + b^2 \right] \amp =\amp \dfrac{d}{dt}\left[ c^2 \right] \\ \amp \amp \\ 2a\dfrac{da}{dt} + 2b\dfrac{db}{dt} \amp =\amp 2c\dfrac{dc}{dt}\\ \end{array} Then plug in the known information and solve. We have \dfrac{da}{dt} = -45, which is negative because the distance from the officer to the intersection is decreasing. We also have \dfrac{dc}{dt} = 25. We can find the distance between the cars at this specific moment: c = \sqrt{(1/2)^2 + (1/2)^2} = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}. \begin{array}{rcl} 2\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(-45\right) + 2\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\dfrac{db}{dt} \amp =\amp 2\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)(25)\\ \amp \amp \\ \dfrac{db}{dt} = 25 \sqrt{2} + 45 \approx 80.3553390593274. \end{array}
For the second part, \dfrac{dc}{dt} = -25. \begin{array}{rcl} 2\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(-45\right) + 2\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\dfrac{db}{dt} \amp =\amp 2\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)(-25)\\ \amp \amp \\ \dfrac{db}{dt} = -25 \sqrt{2} + 45 \approx 9.64466094067262. \end{array}
